25 SECTION 2.2. G.S. 30-3.4 reads as rewritten:
26 "§ 30-3.4. Procedure for determining the elective share.
27 (a) Exercisable Only During Lifetime. – The right of the surviving spouse to file a claim
28 for an elective share must be exercised during the lifetime of the surviving spouse, by the
29 surviving spouse, by the surviving spouse's agent if the surviving spouse's power of attorney
30 expressly authorizes the agent to do so or to generally engage in estate, trusts, and other beneficial
31 interests, or, with approval of court, by the guardian of the surviving spouse's estate or general
32 guardian. If a surviving spouse dies before the claim for an elective share has been settled, the
33 surviving spouse's personal representative shall succeed to the surviving spouse's rights to an
34 elective share.
35 (b) Time Limitations. – A claim for an elective share must be made within six months
36 after the issuance of letters testamentary or letters of administration in connection with the will
37 or intestate proceeding with respect to which the surviving spouse claims the elective share by
38 (i) filing a verified petition with the clerk of superior court of the county in which the primary
39 administration of the decedent's estate lies,and (ii) mailing or delivering a copy of that petition
40 to the personal representative of the decedent's estate. lies. A surviving spouse's incapacity shall
41 not toll the six-month period of limitations.
42 …
43 (e1) Procedure. – An elective share proceeding shall be an estate proceeding and shall be
44 conducted in accordance with the procedures of Article 2 of Chapter 28A of the General Statutes.
45 The verified petition shall be filed by the clerk upon payment of the costs assessed in
46 G.S. 7A-307. An elective share proceeding shall be an estate proceeding and shall be conducted
47 in accordance with the procedures of Article 2 of Chapter 28A of the General Statutes, except as
48 modified or supplemented by the following:
49 (1) Upon the filing of the verified petition, the petition shall be served upon the
50 personal representative in accordance with G.S. 1A-1, Rule 4 of the Rules of
51 Civil Procedure, without issuance of a summons. The petition shall also be
